Going to start a somewhat self-indulgent but mostly self-encouraging thread for the stuff I enjoy/achieve in 2022.

The last two years have just been a groundhog day of readjustment and keeping myself above water, so I’m hoping this can help keep myself on track this year 💭

And here is my Top 20 albums of this year, to round all that off. 

2021 has been one of the hardest years of my life and music’s been a weird part of it this year. I’m thankful to have been able to experience these albums though and I hope next year can be better 🙏 https://t.co/Np3XfRGrC4

Probably the most important big release of this year on a mainstream level, in my (less than humble) opinion, and I hope I can experience all of this with thousands of others next year. One of the only bands I can say that about this year. Gojira are just the best 🖤

1. And my song and album of the year goes to Gojira, who have always been a favourite of mine. Managing to make such a moving, impactful, necessary metal album that touches on what is needed to change the world though, they have helped me get through 2021 more than anyone else https://t.co/Px7yyJzca5
@TimLumb You’ll drive yourself crazy if you don’t soon haha!

2. Not a band, song or album that will work for everyone because of the sheer amount of what goes on but that chaos has been a strange comfort during this year.

There’s also hooks for days all over this. Dollar Signs better bring their live show to the UK asap 🎺 https://t.co/NzsJiACaCB

3. Many people will write this whole album off as novelty but goddamn does this give me so much dumb joy (shock horror). 

As far as I’m concerned, Weezer can keep doing AOR for as long as they want cause this is just wonderful to me 👩‍🎤 https://t.co/E5GoGuYDtc

4. Not an exaggeration on my part to say that I can imagine this song being played on the radio alongside hits from the late 80s and early 90s. 

Absolutely timeless levels of craft to this tune and it’s crazy how there’s no sign of that scale diminishing anytime soon 🖤 https://t.co/y3J1moza0y

5. There are so many bands who have tried to do the “Nirvana thing” in the modern age but very few have nailed it in the last few years as much as Superbloom have, in my not too humble opinion.

Get these guys supporting some big alt rock bands please https://t.co/YfLxls9VFH

6. Of an album that’s chock full of anthems, this one is one of the ones I’ve went back to the most.

Absolutely colossal alt rock songs here and it’s criminal that Teenage Wrist aren’t so much bigger than what they are https://t.co/BIPm0ssczj

7. Very few bands/albums/songs have brought me as much joy this year that Turnstile have. 

Fully onboard with this band taking over the world with their infinitely cool alt-rock take on hardcore. Buzzing to see what comes next for them 👊 https://t.co/y4pzDpCvR6

8. Endless amounts of respect for Ukraine always putting forward something unabashedly themselves for a competition like Eurovision where millions watch.

Still gutted this weird gothy folk/industrial banger didn’t win but it was great seeing such love for total outsiders 🖤🇺🇦 https://t.co/yfFoO8VRg2

9. There are so many Australian bands at the moment totally acing the emo-tinged pop punk thing in the last few years.

Sly Withers were the band that really cemented that for me this year as I’ve just kept coming back to this song (and album) since I first heard it 🇦🇺 https://t.co/anIAQDL7s0

10. Regardless of whether or not you prefer your Deafheaven with or without metal, the fact that they don’t care about anyone’s opinion on that should be admirable to everyone.

It also happens that they are so good at crafting gorgeous melodic dreampop songs as well. In love 😍 https://t.co/0V7P41TIk3

11. Utterly breathtakingly gorgeous, soaring and simultaneously furious atmospheric black metal from Serena Cherry that is made even cooler with its Skyrim theme.

Desperate to see these guys live whenever that can happen 🗡 https://t.co/QfBEFh4EQD

12. Very few albums have stayed on as regular rotation throughout the year than this one and it came out on the very first day of 2021!

This song has became one of my favourites from it. The handclap section that sounds so much like The Darkness is also the ONE 👏 https://t.co/9xcKfy8tCt
@TimLumb A lot of fun! Especially if you’re fond of 80s hardcore 👊

13. One of my favourite musical discoveries in a year where I’ve listened to so many new bands.

Totally love the grungy punk snottiness of these guys and their energy was wicked in the live environment too. So much fun! https://t.co/hk3hErgCJK

14. Riley Hawk is such a badass human being as it is but the fact he also creates this kind of scuzzy, grungy stoner punk with Warish makes me admire him even more

Get this listened to if you wish Nevermind had more dirt under its fingernails! https://t.co/GCv8TkV8Cz

15. Fast paced aggressive yet incredibly fun hardcore punk from South Korea in the vein of Minor Threat and Black Flag.

Enough attitude and baddassery to make this not overly sweet as well. Looking forward to what comes next from them😍 https://t.co/mgxBRb33tz

All about AFI going down a post-punk route and fully ramping up the Cure influences on this one 🦇 https://t.co/AMNg91EhAr

18. Idle Hands were one of the most exciting and interesting metal bands to come out for a while + the band still live up to that description with the new name.

22. Always been a bigger fan of Royal Blood than most people who are into heavier music but I’m strangely even more on board with them going in a dance-rock direction while still keeping the riffs nice and chunky.

Long story short, and kind of as a mantra that I can come back to myself when I’m feeling bad. People care and you are never as alone or different as what your brain tells you you are. I hope we as a society can do better at supporting others. Particularly after this last year ❤️

I finally feel like I’m starting to deal with this in a way that I’ve been needing to for literally years but I’ve always had some excuse or distraction to put me off. It’s really hard but I feel like progress is being made.

After a few weeks of battling with myself, trying to contact a GP and agonising over whether I was “worthy” enough for medical help, I finally got my mental health nurse appointment yesterday and I’m glad that my feelings have been “approved” in a stupid kind of way.

Anyone who knows me at all in real life probably knows I’m a bit rubbish in social scenarios. A lot of that stems from anxiety that I’ve been struggling with for years. This last year has pushed this to crippling levels on most days and I’ve felt low since around November time.

Been wanting to make a personal mental health related tweet for a while but didn’t want to come across as self-important or preachy or trying to get attention. The timing of me getting my appointment on #MentalHealthAwarenessWeek makes me feel like I should tweet about it though.

Once we begin the recovery process from Covid, a referendum *must* be included in this process 🗳

#SP21

Regardless of whether the SNP and Greens form a coalition or not, the mandate for an independence referendum is undeniable. People of all political persuasions should respect this and make their case for/against independence accordingly.

In terms of the votes themselves, I am pleased with the outcome. I have been a bit disillusioned with the SNP lately so the fact that the Greens are now more able than ever to pull them to the left is very reassuring to me

We also now have a parliament that is more representative of what Scotland is. Again, more work is to be done but we should be proud of the steps taken in making parliamentary positions more accessible to all

Regardless of your views on the SNP or independence, the fact that Scotland strongly rejected the racist and fascist right wing opportunists in this election is something to be really damn happy about. We have a lot of work to do on this but this is a promising sign for society

Have been pretty quiet on here over the election because I wanted to largely take in the results and reflect without the drama of the Twitter-sphere affecting my outlook on things. A day later, and I feel more energised and optimistic about politics than I have for the last year
